eir Jewish identity in the medieval Islamic context. In light of this distinctiveness, Ackerman-Lieberman proposes an alternative model for using the Geniza documents as a tool for understanding daily life in the medieval Islamic world as a whole.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aCairo Genizah. 0aCommercial law (Jewish law)xHistoryxTo 1500. 0aCommercial law (Jewish law)xHistoryyTo 1500. 0aJewish merchantsxHistoryxTo 1500xEgypt. 0aJewish merchantszEgyptxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aJewsxIdentityxHistoryxTo 1500xEgypt. 0aJewszEgyptxIdentityxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aPartnership (Jewish law)xHistoryxTo 1500. 0aPartnership (Jewish law)xHistoryyTo 1500. 4aGeniza. 4aS. D. Goitein. 4acommerce. 4aculture. 4aeconomics. 4aidentity. 4apartnerships. 4atrade. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311070398640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804787161zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804787161423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804787161.jpg  a978-3-11-070398-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles